'''Manai Shrine''' (まないじんじゃ, 眞名井神社) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Yamashiro-chō, {{ill|lt=Matsue|Q207321|qid=Q207321|1=Matsue}}, {{ill|lt=Shimane Prefecture|Q132751|qid=Q132751|1=Shimane Prefecture}}. It is one of the {{ill|lt=Oi six shrines|Q11073594|qid=Q11073594|1=Ou district}} and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was village shrine. It is enshrined southeast of Chausuyama, identified with “Kaminahi-no” of the Oi District section in the {{ill|lt=Izumo-no-Kuni Fudoki|Q11395858|qid=Q11395858|1=Izumo no Kuni Fudoki}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
It enshrines {{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|qid=Q813858|lt=Izanagi-no-Kami|1=Izanagi}} and {{ill|lt=Amatsuhikone|Q10940228|qid=Q10940228|lt=Amatsuhikone-no-Mikoto|1=Amatsuhikone}}.

=== History ===
In the Oi District section of ''Izumo-no-Kuni Fudoki'', two shrines are listed: “Manai-sha” (a Shrine Bureau shrine) and “Matsuna-i-sha” (non–Shrine Bureau shrine). The ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' also records “Manai Shrine” in Oi District, Izumo Province. However, this shrine appears as “Izanaki-sha” in ''Izumo Fudoki-shō'' ({{ill|lt=1683|Q7651|qid=Q7651|1=1683}}, {{ill|lt=Tenna|Q1145289|qid=Q1145289|1=Tenna}} 3) and as “Izanagi-sha” in ''Unyōshi'' ({{ill|lt=1717|Q6895|qid=Q6895|1=1717}}, {{ill|lt=Kyōhō|Q1145048|qid=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 2), so in the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}} it was called “Izanagi-sha.” In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}, it was renamed “Manai Shrine.”

It is said that rites of this shrine were handled by the Akigami family, shrine family of {{ill|lt=Kamosu Shrine|Q3192477|qid=Q3192477|1=Kamosu Shrine}}, who served as both priest and ritual-fire attendant, and that shrine buildings of both shrines were built in the same periods<ref>Asakawa (2006), p.39</ref>.

=== Precincts ===
; Haiden
: The present building was erected in {{ill|lt=1934|Q18714|qid=Q18714|1=1934}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 9).
; Honden
: {{ill|lt=Taisha-zukuri|Q387874|qid=Q387874|1=Taisha-zukuri}}. The current building was rebuilt in {{ill|lt=1662|Q7574|qid=Q7574|1=1662}} ({{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 2). It was designated a prefectural tangible cultural property in {{ill|lt=1974|Q2072|qid=Q2072|1=Marcel Hirscher}}.
; Matsuna-i Shrine
: Precinct shrine.

===Cultural properties===
===Shimane Prefecture designated cultural properties===
*Honden - designated in {{ill|lt=1974|Q2072|qid=Q2072|1=Marcel Hirscher}}.

=== Manai Falls ===
East of this shrine is a waterfall called “Manai Falls”<ref>Regarding Manai, in ancient usage “i” (well) could also mean “waterfall” (Seki (2006), p.189).</ref>. ''Unyōshi'' notes “Manai Kōjin” near this waterfall and identifies that place with the Manai-sha of the Fudoki. Water drawn from this basin is said to have been used from ancient times for the sacred-fire succession rite and Niiname-sai of the {{ill|lt=Izumo no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Q11395856|qid=Q11395856|1=Izumo clan}}.

